{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"31652077-00e6-4044-9ed7-3f15e482fc56","content":"The repository is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance based on .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS writes a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Inspect with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check:\n   - SIP may block core dumps — `csrutil status` to verify.\n   - The app must not handle the signal itself (`SIGABRT`, `SIGSEGV`, etc.).\n   - Disk space and permissions on `/cores/`.\n\n6. **Alternative — use `lldb` directly:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) bt          # backtrace\n   (lldb) process save-core /tmp/crash.core\n   ```\n\n**Key difference for NativeAOT:** Since there's no CoreCLR runtime, `createdump` isn't bundled. You rely entirely on the OS-level core dump facilities or `lldb` attach. The resulting core file is a standard Mach-O dump (not a managed minidump), so use `lldb` — not `dotnet-dump` — for analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2df68646-ebad-47eb-9793-c107f4b4dbd3","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"6413:33DFCD:15AE223:192ECF5:69EC1A1F"},"id":"1356a710-1188-4c2f-a459-20b033c28958","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:34:35.063Z","parentId":"21ac9fb8-77ee-46b1-976b-59589ebbfb06"}
